The paper deals with concurrent data structures and their linearizability, which are topics typically covered in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Programming Languages (cs.PL), Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), and Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories of arXiv CS. The paper's focus on reasoning about linearization points using a Hoare-style logic suggests that it may be more relevant to the Programming Languages and Logic in Computer Science sub-categories. However, the paper's emphasis on concurrent data structures and their implementation details, as well as its use of examples from distributed systems, suggest that it may also be relevant to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing and Data Structures and Algorithms sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on verification and correctness suggests that it may also be relevant to the Software Engineering sub-category.
